2. capitis: citizenship in its broadest sense.— poena: cf. ne periret, Ep. X. n.

3. profecti sumus: a regular use of the epistolary perfect-for the present. Cicero is on the point of sailing.—-a. d. 11 K. Mai.: an unusual expression for pridie K. Mazi, but for the same formula, cf. C. l. L. Ι. 902, 979.—pete- bamus: a regular epistolary im- perfect, indicating what would be going on at the time the letter was received. Cf. Intr. 84 c.— aegram . . . corpore: Terentia’s health would seem to have been delicate at the best, if we may judge from Cicero’s earnest words in several letters, ag. Ep. LVIII. and Fam. 14. 22. Cf. also Ep. LVI.

—sic agam: a colloquial phrase, meaning little more than ‘this is the best plan.' Its stereotyped character is shown by the fact that Cicero proceeds to state a plan of action, not for himself but for Terentia.—confirmes . . . adiu- ves-z on the mood and tense, cf. Intr. 84 b. — transactum est, it 's all over; a colloquialism. Actum est is more common3 cf. eg. Att. 5. 15. 13 9. 12. 4, and Plaut. Trz'n. 3083 Ter. A nd. 465.
